function advantageCount(nums1, nums2) {
    const sortedNums1 = [...nums1].sort((a, b) => a - b);
    const res = [];

    for (const num of nums2) {
        let idx = binarySearch(sortedNums1, num);
        if (idx === sortedNums1.length) {
            idx = 0;
        }
        res.push(sortedNums1.splice(idx, 1)[0]);
    }

    return res;
}

function binarySearch(arr, target) {
    let left = 0, right = arr.length;
    while (left < right) {
        const mid = Math.floor((left + right) / 2);
        if (arr[mid] <= target) {
            left = mid + 1;
        } else {
            right = mid;
        }
    }
    return left;
}
```


    The algorithm first sorts the nums1 array. For each number in nums2, we want to find the smallest number in nums1 that is larger than the target number. This can be done using Binary Search or inbuilt functions like upper_bound or higherKey depending on the language. If we find the index of the smallest larger number, we remove it from nums1, and add it to the result array. If no larger number is found, we take the smallest number from nums1 and add it to the result. This ensures we maximize the advantage of nums1 with respect to nums2.

